2. Problem Statement

Operational applications commonly store data in flexible NoSQL databases such as DynamoDB. This allows application teams to evolve their data models quickly, but the resulting records are usually nested and semi-structured.

When this data is copied into the Lakehouse, it may still be stored as a JSON document inside a small number of columns. The data has technically reached the analytics platform, but it is not yet easy for analysts or downstream applications to use.

Creating a usable data product from such data currently requires several manual activities:

* Understanding the source application data model
* Reading DynamoDB entity and bean definitions
* Inspecting the existing Lakehouse ingestion configuration
* Identifying nested objects, arrays and relationships
* Designing normalized tables
* Deciding primary and foreign keys
* Writing PURE model definitions
* Writing materialized-view transformations
* Validating the generated artifacts
* Creating and reviewing repository changes

This process is time-consuming, repetitive and highly dependent on domain knowledge. Different developers may also model the same data differently, leading to inconsistent outputs and additional review effort.

