7. System Architecture

AutoLake consists of four main layers.

7.1 VS Code Extension

The VS Code extension provides the user-facing interface.

It is responsible for:

* Collecting repository and namespace inputs
* Starting the workflow
* Displaying stage progress
* Showing generated schema proposals
* Collecting approvals and corrections
* Displaying validation errors
* Opening the generated merge request

7.2 Pipeline Orchestrator

The orchestrator manages the complete workflow.

It controls:

* Stage execution
* Input and output passing
* Pipeline state
* Error handling
* Retry behaviour
* Approval checkpoints
* Resume-from-failure support

Each stage writes its output to disk before the next stage begins. This makes the workflow inspectable and resumable.

7.3 Extraction and Generation Modules

These modules perform the main technical work.

They include:

* Application repository extractor
* Lakehouse repository extractor
* Intermediate-mapping generator
* Normalization agent
* Summary-matview generator
* PURE generator
* Validation engine
* Repository-delivery module

Some stages are deterministic, while others use an LLM where reasoning is required.

7.4 Tool and Platform Integrations

AutoLake integrates with external systems through controlled tools and APIs.

These integrations include:

* GitLab for repository operations
* Confluence for documentation retrieval
* Internal Lakehouse utilities
* File-system tools
* Validation tools
* LLM services

Sensitive credentials are retrieved from approved secret-management systems and are not written into generated files or logs.

